The following new lead was qualified by Dave at Software Advice. Please feel free to mention Dave's name when you first contact the prospect. Questions about this lead should be sent through the Customer Support App. Replies to this email will not be received.
 
Contact Information
Company name: M.B. Kahn
Contact name: Kara Soles
Job title: Vice President of Business Development
Direct: (803) 227-5236
Email: ksoles@mbkahn.com
Website: http://www.mbkahn.com
Address: 101 Flintlake Road
City: Columbia
State: SC
ZIP code: 29223
Country: United States
Timestamp: 5/31/16 10:13 CDT
 
Company Profile
Segment: Construction - B2B. Industrial construction company that takes on $5M-$100M projects. They self perform some of the work. This is just the industrial division of a larger company. They offer commercial design/build services as well.
Size (Annual Revenue): $51 million to $100 million
Number of Employees: 101 to 500 employees
Number of Users: 2 to 5 users. 3 users to start out. This may roll out to other divisions as well, but for now they're concerned with the industrial division.
 
Project & Requirements Overview
Applications needed: Sales Automation
Key features needed: This buyer wants a system that will track upcoming projects, track sales meetings, track interactions, tag contacts, and pull reports.
Deployment: Not Determined
Currently using: They used to use Act!, but they haven't had it for several years. They use Gmail internally, but many of the people there are synched with Outlook.
Reasons for shopping: Kara was recently brought on to help get the sales efforts organized, and this is one of the big priorities currently.
Who they've evaluated: Act!.
Price expectations: Screened for $80/user/month plus setup costs.
Timeframe: They want to get something in place within a few months.
 
Next Steps
Request: Demo
Product: Cosential
Follow-up instructions: Call between 4 and 5:30 EST.
Contact notes: Kara was tasked by a senior vice president to find something for the core business development team.
Qualified By: Dave

No CRM. Very old school mentality. Tracking leads/opps of most importance. Not too many in depth proposals, more letter proposal types and FOQ. Heavy lead/opp, outlook integration, mobile app, email marketing. Billquick is their accounting software. 3-8 people start with 2 full users and the rest would be CRM users. Driving adoption and getting people to use it is key. Move slow and don't overwhelm with all the bells and whistles. Kerri is a consultant but it seems she'll be working side by side with Stacy Malone as they will both be full users. Demo set for 5/31 at 4pm.

Segment:    Construction - B2B. This is for a plumbing subcontractor and design/build firm with a large engineering and design team that focuses on multifamily and hospitality projects exclusively in the state of California. They are ranked the 7th largest contractors in the nation for their respected trade.
Size (Annual Revenue):    $101 million to $300 million. Over $100M/year.
Number of Employees:    501 to 1,000 employees. Right at 1K.
Number of Users:    6 to 10 users
 
Project & Requirements Overview
Applications needed:    Sales Automation
Key features needed:    He wants to have a digital rolodex of clients, contractors, and vendors. The system should help keep their communication and feedback organized and the correspondence up-to-date in realtime.
Deployment:    Not Determined
Currently using:    Spectrum, Excel, folders. Currently using Outlook companywide. He is open to switching to Gmail for his sales team, for the right system.
Reasons for shopping:    He wants to bring in a CRM solution for his sales guys to track communication with clients easier and more efficiently.
Who they've evaluated:    SalesForce, Dynamics, Hitachi Solutions.
Price expectations:    $125/user/month and $1K/license upfront plus setup costs.
Timeframe:    Next 3 months.

Company Profile
Segment:    Construction - B2B. AEC firm that acts as a general contractor and provides design build services for commercial and public projects.
Size (Annual Revenue):    $26 million to $50 million
Number of Employees:    51 to 100 employees. 85 employees.

Project & Requirements Overview
Applications needed:    Sales Automation
Key features needed:    This buyer is looking for a system that will track prospective projects and will keep track of contacts at owner rep and owner firms, as well as architects and engineering firms managing projects. Price expectations:    Screened for $75/user/month plus setup fees.
Timeframe:    They'll make a decision within 2-3 months.

Company Profile
Segment:    Construction - B2B. Architecture, design, and construction firm.
Size (Annual Revenue):    $6 million to $25 million. $10M.
Number of Employees:    21 to 50 employees. 25 employees.
Number of Users:    2 to 5 users. 3 users.
 
Project & Requirements Overview
Applications needed:    Sales Automation
Key features needed:    Manage separate pipelines for leads that are design only, build only, or design and build. They want to input incoming leads, send email blasts, and track communication through the system. The field sales team needs access through iPads. It would be nice if the system has advanced features such as a website landing page, social media integration, and lead generation.
Deployment:    Web-based
Currently using:    Free trial of Apptivo. Previously used spreadsheets, Outlook for email.
Reasons for shopping:    Apptivo does not offer an iPad app. They are also unable to link tasks and activity to the related contact.
Who they've evaluated:    HubSpot.
Price expectations:    Screened up to $75/user/month plus setup.
Timeframe:    Immediate.

Slam dunk Disco call - They have a home grown DB which they were about to sink another 50-60k into getting it updated so that it actually works.  This DB held current bids and company info.

This client is a perfect fit for Cosential and they are jazzed about it.  Multiple office locations would all be represented in Cosential so there is high potential for good seat counts.  

The have folks that do bids, and folks who do proposals.  Initially they said that their proposals were too custom to have done by us, but I explained how we dynamically pull in custom opp fields and they are now hopeful that they too can leverage Proposal Automation. Not sure I remember what Acctg system they use.  

 

Interested in more information. Sees the benefit of a CRM but not sure if the company is willing to invest. She used to do BD but has moved into a slightly different role. Requested brochure and open to talking further. Disco set for Andy on 4/20.

3 companies. Bottom level. Concrete ready mix plant. 

2nd tier is harkins concrete construction. That company works for other contractors as well as Harkins contractors. Concrete construction company is often on site with other generals. Want to be able to share and manage lead and opportunities. She is the controller. Computer use is acct software? Might look at new acct software so it would be great to integrate but not a deal breaker. Dispatching software, command alcon. Customer info entered in there. Causes some disconnect. Plant, VP/operations manager. He is the main BD person. Assistant plant manager and dispatcher. Majority of business is people coming to them. 6-7 users to start.

In 2005, Alex Hernandez founded Hernandez Consulting in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina to help with New Orleans’ re-building process. Utilizing the firm’s small and disadvantaged business certifications, Hernandez Consulting captured several contracts with federal agencies to provide construction, security and project management services. Since our origination, the firm has developed into a project management firm specializing in construction, architecture, real estate development, and sustainability and energy management consulting.

 

Headquartered in New Orleans, Louisiana; with two additional offices in Miami, Florida and Fayetteville, Arkansas; Hernandez Consulting operates throughout the Southern United States and beyond. Our Offices are staffed with highly trained construction and design professionals to include superintendents, project managers, estimators, architects and administrative personnel. 

 

 

 

Brief call with Andy to qualify and demo is set for 4/12.

Notes - Hello Jeff,

 

We currently use Procore as our construction mgt software and have used Insightly in the past, but to limited results.  We’re considering salesforce simply because I used in the past.  Do you have a demo package or software download to evaluate?  Or maybe a quick demo at our office?

 

Tucker

Hello Jeff – thank you for reaching out.

I would love to implement Cosential, but I know that we won’t be able to set aside the money to do it right now. Do you want to check back in a few months from now?

.  I would love to arrange a short call with you to talk more about Cosential – I am finding that industry-specific CRM’s may be more what we are looking for than other CRM’s like Salesforce or Sage.   I am currently talking with Deltek about their Ajera CRM and would love to see how Cosential compares.

New lead from software advice came in for the same company.

Contact Information
Company name:    CEI Engineering
Contact name:    Lee Gray
Job title:    Coordinator
Office:    (479) 273-9472
Email:    lgray@ceieng.com
Website:    http://www.ceieng.com
Address:    3108 Southwest Regency Parkway, Suite 2
City:    Bentonville
State:    AR
ZIP code:    72712
Country:    United States
Timestamp:    1/27/16 10:13 CST
 
Company Profile
Segment:    Engineering - B2B. This is an architectural and engineering design firm.
Size (Annual Revenue):    $6 million to $25 million. They make $15-$25 million annually.
Number of Employees:    101 to 500 employees. They have 100-110 employees.
Number of Users:    21 to 50 users. They need about 30 users.
 
Project & Requirements Overview
Applications needed:    Sales Automation
Key features needed:    They are looking for a contact management system to track contact information/interactions, schedule follow-ups/reminders, and generate reports. They need a mobile app. They would like to integrate with Ajera if possible.
Deployment:    Web-based
Currently using:    They currently use Ajera for project management with Excel spreadsheets. They use Outlook for email.
Reasons for shopping:    They need something more streamlined and centralized so everybody is on the same page.
Who they've evaluated:    They are just starting the research process and haven't been in contact with any vendors.
Price expectations:    They are open to $35-$65/user/month + setup costs.
Timeframe:    They would like to make a decision in the next few months.
 
Next Steps
Request:    Demo
Product:    Cosential
Follow-up instructions:    Call after 4pm CST.
Contact notes:    Lee is part of the committee that will make the final decision. They are just starting the process and will do demos as they go. She told me they want to narrow the search down to three vendors and reach out on February 18th. I would keep the first call/interaction short.
Qualified By:    Kevin

Roger

Job title:    Assistant Estimator
Direct:    (701) 792-3213
Email:    tinah@constructionengineers.com

Address:    200 North 69th Street
City:    Grand Forks
State:    ND
ZIP code:    58203
Country:    United States
Timestamp:    2/15/16 13:00 CST
 
Company Profile
Segment:    Construction - B2B. This is a design/build firm.
Size (Annual Revenue):    $6 million to $25 million
Number of Employees:    21 to 50 employees. They have 40 employees in the office.
Number of Users:    2 to 5 users. They need 4-5 users.
 
Project & Requirements Overview
Applications needed:    Sales Automation
Key features needed:    They are looking for a sales system to track contact information/interactions/estimates, schedule follow-ups/reminders, and generate sales reports.
Deployment:    Not Determined
Currently using:    They currently use Act! with Outlook for email.
Reasons for shopping:    The system is outdated and they need to upgrade. They want to see what other options are available.
Who they've evaluated:    They have talked to Pipeliner.
Price expectations:    They are open to $35-$65/user/month (I screened for $200+/month) + setup costs.
Timeframe:    They would like to implement this system as soon as they find something they like.
 
Next Steps
Request:    Demo
Product:    Cosential
Follow-up instructions:    Call around 8am CST.
Contact notes:    Tina was tasked by the Scott Craigson, the President, to look into options for a new system. She will be the main point of contact and will return any missed calls/messages.

column28:
Notes from the Demo:

Kathryn Bost- Marketing Director

Craig Stuvek - Marketing

Can I base a report just on prospects?

Chris liked that they don’t have to manually update time per person/job. Wow moment.

Sazan has 85 EE's and growing to 100> Kathryn is ee # 7.

They asked how the IT piece works? - Dan-WE install a connector to your server. That’s it.

Do we work with the implementation manager on what we want on or off? Yes.

 

Dan

1-2k for implementation fee

How long is the implementation process? 1-3 months

 

Craig:

For the project managers is there a CRM package? CRM users companies, contacts, opps and leads.

 

Licensing needs est:

4 full and 10 crm

 

Timeline;

Summer

Web search – CRM that’s oriented to projects. 

 

Your lead process –

Get a lead , do a proposal.  Send the plans.

 

What kind of info do you have in your proposals. 

 

Materials.  Sq footage, price.  Labor, payment.  Quote not a proposal. 

 

Hardwood floor installers.

Quickbooks.  Likely too small. 

We are very small.  7 ppl.

Changing our business model.  Getting bigger, working closer with businesses.  We are expanding and hard to keep track of the info.  Give the installers the tools to find more business.  Using it from the field.  Keep track of the emails. 

 

Change orders.  Painful.  Need to change real time from the field.  Keep everybody on the same page.  Calendar of our projects.  What projects are coming up on what size and schedule?  Need to allocate people. 

My boss suggesting that we can use a system. 

We work with paper notes and reminders.  Stuff gets lost.  Overlooked. 

His job is to get the plans and come up with sq footage and respond to proposal and track the acceptance of that proposal.  Then we have to invoice the materials at 50%.  Need to get that money received and schedule the job.  Then prior to starting installation, we require the next 50% of material.  We go and install.  Then they pay the final balance.  Needs workflow. 

 

Demo – This week.  

 

 

Event Type: demo
Company: Naples Flooring Company
FullName: Alex Ledesma
Email: naplesflooring@gmail.com
Phone: 2392771213
FormURL: http://www.cosential.com/demo/

column27: 3/10 Dan responded to Andy. Said evaluating systems.
column28:
What I want to do.

 

Worked with MS Dynamix in the past.

 

Track and maintain our opportunities and clients.  Central DB.  Basic CRM.  Follow up, etc.  Managing in outlook, no visibility…

 

Assign opps to folks, rank it for go/no go. 

 

Generate a proposal from templates.  Automatically populate some basic info. 

 

Attach that proposal and content to the opp for tracking.

 

Central repository. 

 

Dashboard to see individual metrics and company metrics.

 

Track and nurture future projects.

 

Once it turns into a sale, show the potential of the opp.

 

Looking at an ERP system to then push that info into PM or accounting software. 

 

Access it remotely.

 

6 ppl – one office.  Heyward California.

 

Opening a branch in Modesta. 

 

Send mailers and manage events

 

Target clients

 

Equip sales, and part sales.  Not looking for product lists necessarily…

 

Quoting projects – not huge, we don’t build buildings.  Most projects are weeks long, maybe a month….

 

American Contractor – Vista Viewpoint now owns.  Looking to upgrade to Vista.  Does WAY to much. 

 

Looked at MS CRM…  Too many bells and whistles..

 

Need a dashboard, but that is not too exciting.

 

Owner and all management will be using it, we are all selling.  We all get our hands dirty and sell. 

 

I want to make sure it is simple…

 

Send him a couple demo times for tues and Wed so he can coordinate with his boss, Pete.

Event Type: demo
Company: Bay City Boiler & Engineering Co.
FullName: Don Patten
Email: Dpatten@baycityboiler.com
Phone: 5107863711
FormURL: http://www.cosential.com/demo/

column27: Sent updated proposal to Carrisa without DC cost. Called to confirm this was all she needed and she said yes. Said contract should be signed by EOW
column28:
Notes from Demo -

Past client

How is everything displayed on mobile app?

Can I view all people connected to opportunity on mobile app?

I want!!

Does driving directions integrate with your car GPS?

Mobile note taking important via voice command. Solved every problem she had. She would use all of that.

Business card scanner light interest.

How can we contact people for an event? Perfect with the ability to log and auto updated based on response i.e accepted/declined etc.

Go/No Go - Probabilities to determine marketing/biz dev efforts

"Very organized and powerful. You get out of it what you put into it."

Implementation - fundamentals are already here. We know your business.

"Not reinventing the wheel right now". Efficiency

What do we need to chase after? Good method for scoring and ranking using past data. Go/No GO

Dedicated BD folks. Need more dooer/seller

Tracking RFP important

Disc Call Notes -

Carissa is driving in the rain.

Mobile ap is VERY important.

My company had used Cosential 5 years ago before I was part of it.

They killed it bc they lost their OFA.

I came along and was the sales leader relationship leader. Getting into new markets. Utilized outlook business contact manager. Has manipulated it a lot.

Lots of time on the road. Has to sit in her office

May be others my assistant. He has a lot of responsibilities.

Another office 3 hours away. The VP is doing some sales.

She does the proposals too. Estimating puts the numbers.

Goes back to the office to discuss proposals.

Contact manager sits on Outlook.

For the sake of argument tracking info on jobs.

100 yr old company.

Accubuild Accounting software

Monday at 9 am. Demo - focus on CRM and Mobile - still show the prop automation stuff just to plant the seed.

Event Type: demo
Company: MB Contractors, Inc.
FullName: Carissa Mulahn
Email: cmulahn@mbcontractors.com
Phone: 540 342 6758
FormURL: http://www.cosential.com/demo/

Why now?  Just started pushing in our org on Biz Dev.  New role for PMs to be responsible for getting work.

 

We use Outlook contacts for referencing.  It is hard to use and out of date.  How do we do it efficiently.

 

Just trying to line up some options.  Should we even go this route.

 

Very early and beginning stage.

 

CRM use case is main need.

 

Don’t see the need for the FDC.

 

Marketing and biz dev keeping their lanes straight. 

 

Outlook and spreadsheets.  Some people use third party apps.

 

6 office locations in 4 states.  We need to be on the same page.  Cant walk to eachothers office. 

 

Management is not that interested in accountability. – not an explicit need.

 

Small group – We SHOULD be doing this everyday, but they really don’t. 

 

RFPs responding is how we win business. 

 

3 Biz Dev

4 on Marketing Team (everybodys job to find new deals)

40 PM’s – Doing their job and finding new work. 

 

Outlook Shop

 

InFocus – accounting system. 

 

Tracking the RFP process – who did the interview, when, what happened, follow up. 

 

Lets look at prop automation.  Light interest. 

 

Friday.

 

 

Contact Information
Company name:    Thrasher
Contact name:    Caroline Marion
Job title:    Marketing Coordinator
Office:    (304) 624-4108
Direct:    (304) 326-6380
Email:    cmarion@thrashereng.com
Website:    http://www.thrashereng.com
Address:    600 White Oaks Boulevard
City:    Bridgeport
State:    WV
ZIP code:    26330
Country:    United States
Timestamp:    2/1/16 07:53 CST
 
Company Profile
Segment:    Engineering - B2B. Engineering, architecture, and site construction firm.
Size (Annual Revenue):    $51 million to $100 million
Number of Employees:    101 to 500 employees. 300 employees.
Number of Users:    51 to 100 users. They expect that they'll need it for marketing, administration, and project managers, so that comes to close to 100 people. They may make some decisions to narrow it to fewer though.
 
Project & Requirements Overview
Applications needed:    Sales Automation
Key features needed:    This buyer wants a system that will track clients more effectively. They need to track interactions and followups, keep client notes, track their project pipeline, and coordinate communication. They don't need lead management features.
Deployment:    Not Determined
Currently using:    They have InFocus for accounting and it has an account management module.
Reasons for shopping:    Their system can't be changed or customized at all because its intended purpose is primarily accounting. They want to be able to use something that's a better fit for those dealing with clients.
Who they've evaluated:    Nothing yet.
Price expectations:    Screened for $75/user/month plus setup in the five figures.
Timeframe:    They'll make a decision sometime in 2016, but can't narrow it down beyond that.
 
Next Steps
Request:    Price Quote
Product:    Cosential
Follow-up instructions:    Afternoons are the best time to call.
Contact notes:    Caroline was tasked by the firm partners to do the research on this. They will make the final decision.
Qualified By:    Dave

We heard about it last year, watched a couple webinars.  Now its better timing.

 

Already use Dynamix – implemented in early 2013.   Looking to replace.

 

Everyone feels like we aren’t using it to our potential.

 

Square peg, round hole. 

 

Marketing Manager – been here 10 years.  Used to sales support – doing proposals.

 

Involved in the Dynamix implementation. 

 

Selfishly excited about Proposal stuff. 

 

2 ppl doing it now,

 

Axs db trying to track processes. 

 

Sales team needs to focus on the CRM stuff. 

 

Old process – Salesman fills out estimating request form, goes to Gina and to the estimator, Handwritten notes, Monday meeting, Monday meeting.

 

Dynamix helped this process a bit…

Aussie

 

Referred to us by a review page.  Software Advice.

 

I understanding. 

 

Situation is – We already have a PM software.  Spectrum.  Accounting and PM. 

 

What we need is the CRM.  And database for your clientele. 

 

Jason is the Biz Dev Director – Sales responsibilities. 

 

Jason does the proposals as well.  Coordinates with other.

 

His role is to make the intro – depending on the project type, the relationship will be managed by different people. 

 

Had a couple calls – Sage – Started talking to J2 but it wasn’t compatible.  Bullhorn was going well…  BUT, the guy got agitated and didn’t appreciate the constructive critism. 

 

Office 365. 

 

Has used CRM for a long time – former recruiter.

 

Live demo and costs. – 5 users likely.  Jason will be the power user. 

 

Really hoping for simplicity of use.  Married up with Outlook. 

 

Wants to move.

Call and set up demo. See activity interest.

Formerly US Engineer Company – implemented Cosential while I was there.  Helped implement and used heavily

With US Eng Through June of 15.

Joined Raceline in August – BD Manager – call on the big companies – tracking down projects

Engieering, fabrication

250 mi rev

2 business units

Biz unit 1 - manufacturing – can manufacturer.  Our company built the plant that made your can.  – pretty small industry and they know who is who – don’t think they need CRM.  The sharepoint solution was a driver b/c it was very cheap and was supposed to get them off of spreadsheets.

Biz unit 2 - process and energy group = this is Petes group – fairly new – new people - 5 ppl - Pete (BD), John(manager of biz unit), Miranda (Cosnetial potential OFA and group admin) Joe (BD) and Rob (BD)  All 5 would be full users.  

Guy who was supposed build the Sharepoint stuff has spit.  Project bombed.  Never paid him so nothing lost but time.  alot of time.  

Pete told the owner that he used Cosneital and that it was awesome.  Liked the concept but couldn’t sell the Can side on the idea of a more expensive crm.

"No way that sharepoint can get close to what you do"

So now boss has given the green light to look at us.  Spend a little money. 

Gonna look at other options but heavily favoring Cosential due to past use. 

Can Biz unit guys may be on board from day one due to the sharepoint fiasco but in the past said they didnt want to spend real money. 

Pete is using outlook only for his current d2d activities.

 

Pete - Really liked the pipeline and opp management.

 

Opp projects to real bids. - performance reporting

 

Managing a dozen projects now and has no idea how they are progressing.

 

No proposal automation upfront - may want to plant the seed.  

 

Raceline should be a good fit for proposal automation.  Lots of very similar proposals. Gaining pete's interest.

Pete wants to help us sell John.

US Eng was using pipeline data for forecasting.  CFO has a program he uses for forecasting, wins and losses.  Excel or access.

Accounting software – not sure.  Part of the reason they balked at Cosential. - didnt want crm data flowing into acct system.  I explained how it works.  

Send Proposal info – build a plan with Pete to show John pricing and implementation timeline. 

John would then try to sell it to the can side.

Show some cool sample reports.  Forecasting up to the main office.  How far forward looking?  For the year or more.  Bi weekly activity report – opps and current opp status. 

Pete will send me the report – and we will show John how to do it in Cosneital.

Leah (prounonced with an “A”)

We don’t have tools.  No crm and no structured data for proposals. 

No marketing database – just an excel spreadsheet – costs, projects, personell, etc.

Its necessary bc we are growing.  There has been resistance.  Excel is working OK for us…  to find projects – not everyone is onboard with technology. 

She is Office coordinator – helps with proposals and file keeping and photo shoots, website admin, PR agency.  Event planning.  kinda everything.

Outlook for contact management.  Excel sheet to track who is talking to who. 

Firm type – Architecure  - 31 ppl, - no marketing team, outsourced PR (the lead PM on the project team takes the reigns on a proposal.  And Leah helps coordinate the info.  Word of mouth is big, so haven’t had to chase much…  howerver things are changing and marketing is more important.  Need to be in front of new people.

Ajera – integration sounds awesome. shes pumped about it and loved the story about spiting them...

Wants to hear story about client meeting use case in the demo finding projects to bid real time.  .  

Grow slow – this your future.

Her colleagues don’t think our capabilities exists.  Wow them.  

How we win -Growth is on the cusp.  Need to address it now and grow with it.
